title: GoT: The Long Night (spoilers)
body:
Finally got around to watch this episode.

Jaime and Brienne fighting along side each other with the two swords made from Ned Stark’s sword Ice, that was just everything. And their boy Podrick right beside them hanging in there.

Sandor rushing to save Arya, she’s his kid, he’s not fooling anyone.

Shout out to my boys Tormund, Gendry, Grey Worm and Sam. Especially Sam, he was scarred shit-less from the beginning and saw Edd die right in front of him, but he kept on fighting.

Love the moments with Sansa and Tyrion in the crypts. I have a hard time deciding who Tyrion respects and admires the most: Sansa or Daenerys.

Great redemption for Theon. After all the shit he has done and all the shit he has been through, he fought to the very end protecting his true home. And for once Bran was actually kind to give Theon the words he needed to hear, so that the boy who ran away scarred from his uncle last season, died while charging straight for the Night King.

Lyanna Mormont, Oh my beautiful fierce little she-bear. Right from the first time we met her she made it clear she was a tough bad-ass, so dying while taking down an undead giant, best way for her to go out. 

Arya became the one to slay the Night King. Jon tried charging straight at him but got stopped by his own fallen soldiers. Dany tried roasting him with dragon fire and he just shrugged it off. Arya can rightfully call herself kingslayer now.

I feel like Jon and Dany where a bit sidelined in this episode, spending most of it riding the dragons. Not that it wasn’t amazing seeing them flying and fighting the Night king on the undead Viserion. And Jon facing the undead dragon head on at the end was pretty bad-ass.

The one that was most emotional to me was Jorah. Jorah loved Dany, he vowed to protect her to the end and he did. Dying in Dany’s arms was the death he had wanted, and seeing Dany cry (for the first time in like, ever) over his death while Drogon lands next to her, was really powerful.

It’s gonna be hard for the finale of this series to top this episode.

question: See I thought Sansa was playing Tyrion you know “men do stupid things for women” I think she doesn’t trust him and can’t believe he would be dumb enough to believe Cersei when she knew him to be clever so thinks he’s aiding Cersei, she has to play the game because others around her still are and being naive got her in terrible situations before. I also think her distrust of Dany is logical she and Jon fought hard to regain the North and now a foreign queen is asking her to pledge fealty
answer: yeah her distrust is completely understandable, definitely. she has every right to be distraustful given her history with rulers. And Sansa is most definitely smart enough to manipulate Tyrion, maybe Sansa is even the one to find out about Tyrion’s betrayal of Dany by getting him to full and completely trust her with every fibre of his being. And she won’t be happy he’s working with cersei so I think we see where that’ll go. She’s good at playing the game, and she’s going to fucking win in any major or minor way.

summary: Ok game of thrones spoilers below for 8.3
body:
Ok game of thrones spoilers below for 8.3

If you’re still reading at this point I don’t want to hear any whining about spoilers, this is ample chance to look away.

Anyway, does anyone else feel like Arya should have died killing the Night King? Like yes, we don’t have any idea what’s coming next and her role in the battle against Cersei so if I’m proved wrong I am more than happy to eat these words, but I don’t see where her storyline goes from here other than down.

There were numerous other characters whose destiny was to get Arya in front of the NK so she could kill him, and then died because that was their job. If Arya was the same, and her destiny was to kill the NK then that would make sense too, and it would also be an actual serious death in the battle for Winterfell, and let’s face it there weren’t any which for a battle that size is ????

Characters like Berec and Lyanna were cool and liked by fans, and they do kinda matter to the story, but nothing as serious as a death of a Stark or a Lannister or another dragon.

If Arya was mortally wounded by the Night King and then with her dying breaths managed to do her dagger trick, mirroring Lyanna’s because you know GoT loves it’s symmetry, that would have added a lot more weight to the episode and would have added something to the episode that it was missing (other than lighting).

Plus it would prevent the storyline where they just go “hmm, what do we do to defeat Cersei? Oh easy peasy, we send the assassin that could adopt the appearance of anyone, poison Cersei and Euron and then we win with minimal casualties, why don’t we do this given there is 0 downsides here?”.

summary: They gave Lyanna a perfect ending, the smallest of all killing the tallest of all, but Iam still mourning. Dammit she was good....
body:
They gave Lyanna a perfect ending, the smallest of all killing the tallest of all, but Iam still mourning. Dammit she was good. The bear cub more fierce than any. Her mother is waiting for her on the Bear island, proud of her daughter. Lyanna Stark is going to hug her and thank her for what she had done for her family. Songs will be sang in her memory, of the little bear slaying the giant.

Goodbye Lyanna Mormont
